To implement Swagger in a Spring Boot application, you can use Springdoc OpenAPI,
 which is the recommended way as of Spring Boot 2.6+.

‚úÖ Step-by-Step: Add Swagger (Springdoc OpenAPI 3) to Spring Boot
üì¶ 1. Add Maven Dependency

Add this to your pom.xml:
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
    <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId>
    <version>2.2.0</version>
</dependency>

‚ñ∂Ô∏è 2. Run Your App and Open Swagger UI

After starting the app, visit:
http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html
 or /http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui/index.html

 This will auto-generate Swagger UI for all your REST APIs.

 ‚∏ª

 üìò 3. Use Annotations for Better Docs

 Annotate your controllers and models for clear documentation:
----------------
 Example: Controller
 @RestController
 @RequestMapping("/api/users")
 public class UserController {

     @GetMapping("/{id}")
     @Operation(summary = "Get user by ID", description = "Returns a user for the given ID")
     public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
         // logic
     }

     @PostMapping
     @Operation(summary = "Create a new user")
     public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
         // logic
     }
 }
 -----------------
Example: Model
 public class User {
     @Schema(description = "User's unique ID")
     private Long id;

     @Schema(description = "Full name of the user")
     private String name;
 }

 ------------

‚∏ª

‚öôÔ∏è 4. (Optional) Customize OpenAPI Info
@Configuration
public class OpenAPIConfig {

    @Bean
    public OpenAPI customOpenAPI() {
        return new OpenAPI()
            .info(new Info()
                .title("My Application API")
                .version("1.0")
                .description("This is the API documentation for MyApp"));
    }
}

üîí 5. Enable Swagger in Production (Optional)

By default, Springdoc is enabled in all environments.
If you want to disable in production, control it via profiles:
# application-prod.yml
springdoc:
  api-docs:
    enabled: false
  swagger-ui:
    enabled: false
  ‚úÖ You‚Äôre Done!

  Now you have:
  	‚Ä¢	Interactive Swagger UI
  	‚Ä¢	OpenAPI JSON spec at /v3/api-docs
  	‚Ä¢	Clean API documentation with zero extra work

  ‚∏ª

  üì¶ Bonus (if you‚Äôre using Spring Security):

  Add this to permit Swagger endpoints:
  .antMatchers("/v3/api-docs/**", "/swagger-ui/**", "/swagger-ui.html").permitAll()